    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-04-13T04:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-04-13T04:45:00-05:00" n="360"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                <head>360. Telegram 2042 From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Afghanistan</gloss>
                    to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d360fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss
                            target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> AFG. Secret; <gloss target="#t_Exdis1"
                            >Exdis</gloss>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d360fn2">On instructions, the Embassy replied
                        to Daud’s initiative.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Kabul</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1972-04-13T09:45:00+00:00">April 13, 1972, 0945Z</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subj:</head>
                    <item>Afghanistan-Response to Prince Daud</item>
                </list>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>REF:</head>
                    <item>(A) State 56321 (B) Kabul 1806</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Acting under my instructions, EmbOff gave Wahid Abdullah April 11 response
                        indicated para 8, ref B, minus point three repeat three. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SAW2">Wahid</persName> took careful notes. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SAW2">Wahid</persName> immediately stated that there was no
                        answer to question whether dialogue could continue. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SAW2">Wahid</persName> was pleased to learn that dialogue
                        could continue through him and <gloss target="#t_Emboff1"
                        >EmbOff</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Again on my instructions, <gloss target="#t_Emboff1">EmbOff</gloss> then
                        made point suggested para 3, ref A, concerning continuing <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">US</gloss> relations with Afghanistan over years as his
                        “personal and informed opinion.”</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>During conversation <gloss target="#t_Emboff1">EmbOff</gloss> asked how
                        change in government might occur especially in view wahid’s earlier
                        statement that Prince Daud could never take any action which would further
                        divide Afghanistan. <persName corresp="#p_SAW2">Wahid</persName> responded:
                        (a) Daud still adheres to this principle; (b) some members royal family
                        “would favor Daud’s return;” and (c) Marshal Shah Mali Khan and wife have
                        for some time been actively working to effect reconciliation between His
                        Majesty and Princes Daud and Naim.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>For first time in several years I recently saw Princes Daud and Naim at
                        public affair (wedding receiption for Dr. Aziz Seraj’s daughter) and made
                        point of speaking briefly to both. <persName corresp="#p_SAW2"
                            >Wahid</persName> told <gloss target="#t_Emboff1">EmbOff</gloss> in
                        response question, that Princes attended because groom was son of Daud’s
                        former Minister of Interior <pb facs="d360-02" n="2" xml:id="d360-02"/> and
                        is now protege of Daud.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Rumors now cropping up in various Kabul circles about possibility that
                        Daud may reenter political arena.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRG1">Neumann</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
